If Vi is Caitlyn’s gateway into the “real world,” and all the faults and beauty that comes with it, then that also means acknowledging somethings a system needs to be dismantled before it can be changed for the better.

I hate it when people act like it’s totally fine for Caitlyn to convince Vi she’s better off without Jinx. Or that people like Vi and Ekko shouldn’t try to fight against the system, but instead work with it. It’s completely naive— like /Caitlyn/.

Tbh this is what makes their future romantic relationship so compelling to me. There’s a serious divide between them, both in their separate experiences in life and where their loyalties lie. Overcoming that divide, or at least, loving each other in spite of it all is so powerful

ALSO I wanna point out how so many people gloss over the huge power imbalance between Caitlyn and Vi. I love Caitvi, but it annoys be how people water them down to uwu wholesome lesbians, nothing problematic here™️. The ending of Act 3 only complicates their relationship further. https://t.co/HV5J8YRhK1

And yes it’s be forced bc unless she goes her own way, Vi doesn’t exactly have many options. No friends, no family, no where to go. Joining the enforcers would be a means to an end— like finding jinx, trying to do something good along the way

But I really wish it wouldn’t bc it’s be fucking tragic and it pisses me off. Vi being forced to join a group that serves the system which ruined her life before she was even born is horrible and I don’t get why people don’t realize that.

But that doesn’t change Zaun’s rightful anger and fear of the enforcers. It won’t change what the enforcers image means for the people there, both good and bad. 

I can see why Vi would eventually join the enforcers for a multitude of reasons, and it’s probably going to happen—

Even if Caitlyn doesn’t become this way, trying to fix something that’s inherently corrupted and only serves to suit the Council’s whims, is incredibly naive. Grayson wasn’t a bad person, I’m sure there are “good” enforcers, Caitlyn might actually improve the enforcers—
I think Caitlyn absolutely can be corrupted. For ex: Jayce, he was an idealist who wasn’t motivated by power or money, and still fell down the whole of Zaunites being untrustworthy and dangerous.

Hot take but people saying Zaun shouldn’t be free and should continue to monitored by enforcers, even under Caitlyn’s reform, are weird as hell. How are you gonna call independence naive, but go ahead and say that reforming a system which was built on literal oppression isn’t?

Ripping the boy off of Jinx (he’d forgotten his own strength), before quietly threatening him. Making his point by digging one of Jinx’s sharp tools into his side. Mylo grew weary of both him and Jinx after that.
At some point, when one of their many sibling spats turns a bit too physical, with Mylo grabbing at Jinx, pulling her hair— Silco found himself marching up to them.

Silco sees it clear as day, the cruel taunts and mean spirited pranks seem to strip down Jinx like nothing else. 

Silco has often found his little one alone, crying and hitting herself as she mutters incoherently in the dark, after being around her brother. That simply won’t do.
Silco doubts there’s any true maliciousness in him, boys of his age are often as pig headed as they are undisciplined. That still doesn’t excuse the relentless bullying Mylo imparts on Jinx.

Silco listens to all her troubles, her fears and insecurities. He’s patient with his advice, tries to comfort her in his own way. Still, there are certain aspects of Jinx’s life he finds unpleasant, boarding on unacceptable. Case in point: Mylo.

Soon enough, her new android is all she wants to talk about. She never really clicked well with other children besides Ekko before, now she clings to Silco and wants to bring him along everywhere she goes.
If her little sister is happy and less destructive than that should be a good thing… but still Vi feels like her and Powder are drifting further and further apart.

Vi has walked in on Jinx sitting in Silco’s lap one too many times for her own liking. Their growing “relationship” makes her uneasy, but she can’t place why. Maybe it’s the way Silco’s eyes track her sisters every movement, always silently and keenly aware of Powder.

It never closes, which makes it hard for him to move it sometimes. 

Jinx had no idea any of it was hurting him until one day, after a particularly painful adjustment, he gripped *hard* at her ankle and practically snarled at her. She tried to be more gentle after that.

Jinx constantly repairing or doing maintenance on Silco. He’s *her* android afterall, she’s gotta take care of him. Sitting in his lap as she resets the quiet ticking gears in his face and replaces the chem fluid for the damaged eye.
Jinx is surprised to learn he can smoke even with artificial lungs. And the fact that he can smell at all, as well as taste and even eat unlike other androids.

Jinx slowly cueing into what each of Silco’s micro expressions mean, his thought process, knowing what makes him tick gives her a thrill. For instance, dhe notices Silco likes the scent of certain cigar smoke. So, she steals him a box.

The closer they get, the more he starts to remember… 

Jinx likes the way he talks. It’s slow and deliberate, his accent is unfamiliar but pleasant to hear.

She asks him questions about androids and where he came from. Silco tries his best to answer, but doesn’t remember much. He knows a long time ago he worked in the mines, androids often are utilized where the toxic gases of the undercity are unbearable for humans.

Silco finds her utterly endearing. Her erratically punk artwork she vandalizes on anything she can. Her genius intelligence she hides underneath childlike demeanor. Even the bratty way she talks and acts when it’s just the two of them.

She even makes him little gifts. Trinkets to make sure he remembers her (not that he could ever forget his little one). Jinx’s affections melts something inside him, he almost starts to crave it when they aren’t together.

Silco is completely out of depth whenever Jinx is physically affectionate, but he attempts to reciprocate, or at the very least let’s her do as she pleases. Androids aren’t generally treated gently or kindly, let alone ones as ugly and damaged as him.
Holds her when she breaks down or wakes from a nightmare. Once Jinx realizes how warm androids are, she starts cuddling close to him all the time.

Slowly, as they build a relationship, he does more things for her. Like making her meals and bringing her snacks as she tinkers on her gadgets, brushes her hair before braiding two ropes. He tracks her medications. Gives her advice when she asks.

After all, everyone else works, while Jinx is still in that vague category of time thats either “too young” or “too much trouble”. So she talks to him rather than talking to herself, and she’s surprised that he always responds with a sharp and wry wit of his own.
At first, Silco being there was mostly for Jinx to have someone to talk to. Left to her own devices, Jinx might just fret herself into a violent episode.

Something resembling pain pulses from his damaged eye day and night, always lingering, clouding his thoughts. He finds open waters revolting even though it makes him feel calm. And worst yet, he feels a strike of fear whenever Jinx’s father, Vander, looks his way….
Despite not having any memory of how he was broken before, Silco is still haunted by it. He has static dreams, or maybe nightmares are what they’re called, ones where he’s sinking in black liquid.

Vi (who was hesitant to pass her baby’s sister off to an android in the first place) isn’t happy with Jinx’s choice, she tries to be understanding. But— why did she have to pick such a creepy looking one? And an outdated model? She figures it’s just part of her sisters oddities.

Vander looks utterly disturbed when he sees his youngest walking into The Last Drop, happily holding hands with Silco. The android has no reaction to him, so he doesn’t say anything, deciding to just keep a careful watch on them.

Jinx chose him only bc she thought he looked cool and planned to disassemble him in order to use his parts for her own projects the first chance she got. She didn’t expect to (eventually) become so completely dependent on Silco or to care for him so deeply.

Silco is an older android model that was once broken. He’s been rebuilt, but still has “scars” and damaged parts (like his brass and black eye socket). He looks different than all the other newer models, which look too human, and that intrigues her.
Jinx’s mental illnesses are becoming too much of a handful to deal, so Vander decided to pay the extra expense and purchase an android to take care of her. He lets her pick.
